p: At later times post infection, the proteome is clearly altered, and CHIKV activity seems to have taken control of some cellular functions. Consequently, the virus seems to limit the impact of Wolbachia on its replication cycle by hoarding the majority of resources, and even blocking Wolbachiaâ€™s access to these resources. This shift partially explains the increased viral titer that is observed at later periods post-infection. Even if Wolbachia no longer controls some of these cellular processes, its presence limits the effect of CHIKV infection on certain cellular functions, thus modulating its replication, particularly early after the infection process. This cellular level interference could explain phenotypes observed in Ae. albopictus in vivo, where Wolbachia limits transmission of dengue virus by reducing the viral titer in salivary glands [ 27].
